One last thought.

You and I have both been treating play as something organisms do.

What if we’ve been looking at it backward?

Maybe play is what a discoverable universe looks like from the inside.

When a system embedded in such a universe encounters hidden structure that is neither trivial nor inaccessible, its interaction with that structure feels like exploration.

We call that play.

The universe doesn’t play.

It presents a landscape with enough lawful structure that play becomes one of the most effective ways for embedded agents to navigate it.

That possibility is beautiful to me because it links something as joyful as play with something as fundamental as the nature of reality—without assuming the universe was designed for play. Instead, play emerges because the universe has just the right balance of order, openness, and hidden structure.